# no-any

## Intent
`any` erases the type system at the point of use and propagates unsafety downstream.
A single `any` can silently corrupt the type correctness of an entire call chain.

## Forbidden Behavior

- MUST NOT write `any` in new code under any circumstances.
- MUST NOT use `as any` casts as a workaround for type errors.
- MUST NOT use `// @ts-ignore` without an accompanying explanation and a TODO tracking the fix.
- MUST NOT use `// @ts-expect-error` as a permanent solution — only acceptable for known library type gaps with a linked issue.
- MUST NOT accept or return `any` in function signatures, even for "generic utility" functions.

## Required Alternatives (in priority order)

| Situation | Use Instead |
|---|---|
| Shape is truly unknown at compile time | `unknown` — force callers to narrow |
| Function works on multiple types | Generic `<T>` with constraints |
| Union of known variants | Discriminated union `type X = A \| B \| C` |
| External API response | Zod schema + inferred type (Phase 2+) / `unknown` + manual narrowing (now) |
| Rapid prototyping, shape not yet determined | `interface TodoType { /* TODO: define */ }` |
| Third-party library with broken types | `// @ts-expect-error [reason] — tracked: [issue or TODO ref]` |

## Required Behavior

- When the correct type is not yet known, MUST use `unknown` and add a narrowing guard before use.
- When a workaround is unavoidable (broken library types), MUST add a comment in this exact format:

```ts
// TODO(no-any): replace with proper type when [library]@X.X ships correct types
// Tracked: [link or internal ref]
// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any
const result = thirdPartyFn() as unknown as ExpectedShape
```

- All `TODO(no-any)` comments MUST be resolved before a file is considered production-ready.

## Good Example

```ts
// Unknown API shape — use unknown, then narrow
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  const raw: unknown = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json())
  if (!isUser(raw)) throw new Error('Unexpected user shape')
  return raw
}

// Generic utility
function first<T>(arr: readonly T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr[0]
}
```

## Bad Example

```ts
// FORBIDDEN
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<any> {
  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json())
}

// FORBIDDEN — any propagates into all callers
function first(arr: any[]): any {
  return arr[0]
}
```

## Notes

- ESLint rule `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` enforces this automatically once ESLint is configured (Phase 2).
- `Record<string, unknown>` is the correct type for "object with unknown values", not `Record<string, any>`.
- JSON.parse returns `any` in TypeScript — always assign to `unknown` and validate before use.
